    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-08-17T14:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-08-17T14:30:00-05:00" n="275"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d275">
                <head>275. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d275fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives and Records Administration, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1967-69, <gloss
                            target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>-US. Secret. Drafted by Cheslaw and
                        approved in <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss> on August 21. The memorandum is
                        Part 1 of 2. The meeting was held in the Secretary’s office.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1967-08-17T15:30:00-04:00"
                            >August 17, 1967, 3:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Viet-Nam</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DSP1">Sir Patrick Dean</persName>, British
                        Ambassador</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>Irving Cheslaw</persName>, <gloss target="#t_EUR1"
                            >EUR</gloss>/BMI</item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DSP1">Dean</persName> said that the President
                    yesterday had given him a full account of the bombing policy,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d275fn2">No record of this meeting was found.</note> had assured him
                    nothing was new, and had indicated that this present program would probably end
                    by mid-September. <persName corresp="#p_DSP1">Sir Patrick</persName> noted that
                    the call to come to the White House had coincided with instructions from London
                    to try to see the President on this subject. <persName corresp="#p_DSP1">Sir
                        Patrick</persName> asked if the Secretary saw better prospects on the
                    diplomatic front after mid-September.</p>
                <p>The Secretary replied that hardly a week went by without an effort to test Hanoi,
                    but the reactions continued to be negative.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_DSP1">Sir Patrick</persName> asked if we had any reason to
                    think that increasing the military pressure would help. The Secretary replied
                    that there was no reason to think decreasing the pressure would make a
                    difference. As for the previous limits on our bombing program, we imposed these
                    limits ourselves. Meanwhile, the North Vietnamese have been using the area in
                    the far north as a safe haven for their logistical buildup. The Secretary said
                    that the other governments with troops in South Viet-Nam attached great
                    importance to our bombing in the North.</p>
            </div>
